                            <h1>
                            &ldquo;Overcome &hellip; Even As I Also Overcame&rdquo;
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <div class="byline" id="">
				<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p3" class="">Elder Neal A. Maxwell</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p" class="">Of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles</p>
			</div>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            
                            <blockquote class="intro dontHighlight">
                                        <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/neal-a-maxwell?lang=eng">
                                                        <img id="talkPhoto" src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/leaders/neal-a-maxwell-10.jpg" alt="Neal A. Maxwell" class="img-decor">
                                                    </a>
                                        
                                        
                                        
                                    </blockquote>
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">03213_000_026</span>
			<div class="figure">
				
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p4" class="">Events and circumstances in the last days make it imperative for us as members of the Church to become more grounded, rooted, established, and settled (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/col/1.23?lang=eng#22" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Col. 1:23</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/col/2.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Col. 2:7</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/2-pet/1.12?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Pet. 1:12</a>). Jesus said to His disciples, &ldquo;settle this in your hearts, that ye will do the things which I shall teach, and command you&rdquo; (<a href="http://scriptures.byu.edu/getscrip.php?ID=32301">JST, Luke 14:28</a>). If not so settled, the turbulence will be severe. If settled, we will not be &ldquo;tossed to and fro,&rdquo; [<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/eph/4.14?lang=eng#13" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Eph. 4:14</a>] whether by rumors, false doctrines, or by the behavioral and intellectual fashions of the world. Nor will we get caught up in the &ldquo;talk show&rdquo; mentality, spending our time like ancient Athenians &ldquo;in nothing else, but either to tell, or to hear some new thing&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/acts/17.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Acts 17:21</a>). Why be concerned with the passing preferences of the world anyway? &ldquo;For the fashion of this world passeth away&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-cor/7.31?lang=eng#30" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Cor. 7:31</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p5" class="">However, we cannot be thus settled in doing what Jesus has commanded <span class="emphasis">unless</span> we are first settled about Him. If Jesus were only a man, albeit a very good man, His counsel is merely that of a meridian moralist. It is quite another thing, however, for the Creator of multiple worlds, whose central concern is our individual happiness, to command, &ldquo;Thou shalt not commit adultery.&rdquo; [<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ex/20.14?lang=eng#13" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ex. 20:14</a>] Our task, therefore, is to &ldquo;reconcile [ourselves] to the will of God, and not to the will of &hellip; the flesh&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/10.24?lang=eng#23" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 10:24</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p6" class="">The poet-prophet Jacob witnessed among Church members how covenant-breaking wounded &ldquo;delicate minds&rdquo; and how hearts were &ldquo;pierced with deep wounds&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/jacob/2.9,35?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Jacob 2:9, 35</a>). He was &ldquo;weighed down&rdquo; and so heavy with sorrow because some members esteemed their covenants so lightly (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/jacob/2.3?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Jacob 2:3</a>). As I witness some of today&rsquo;s walking wounded, I understand Jacob&rsquo;s feelings as never before!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p7" class="">Some Church members, alas, are neither reconciled to the will of God nor are they sufficiently settled as to their covenants.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p8" class="">Some unworthily covenant afresh, partaking of the broken bread while having broken their covenants of marriage.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p9" class="">Some give of their time yet withhold themselves, being present without giving of their presence and going through the superficial motions of membership instead of the deep emotions of consecrated discipleship.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p10" class="">Some try to get by with knowing only the headlines of the gospel, not really talking much of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://jesuschrist.lds.org/">Christ</a> or rejoicing in Christ and esteeming lightly His books of scripture which contain and explain His covenants (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/25.26?lang=eng#25" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 25:26</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p11" class="">Some are so proud they never learn of obedience and spiritual submissiveness. They will have very arthritic knees on the day when every knee shall bend. There will be no gallery then to play to; all will be participants!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p12" class="">Maintaining Church membership on our own terms, therefore, is not true discipleship.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p13" class="">Real disciples absorb the fiery darts of the adversary by holding aloft the quenching shield of faith with one hand, while holding to the iron rod with the other (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/eph/6.16?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Eph. 6:16</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/15.24?lang=eng#23" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 15:24</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/27.17?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 27:17</a>). There should be no mistaking; it will take both hands!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p14" class="">Real disciples are also, precept by precept and experience by experience, becoming ever more like the Master they serve. We can neither be the woman nor the &ldquo;man of Christ&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/hel/3.29?lang=eng#28" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Hel. 3:29</a>) unless we are coming to have the &ldquo;mind of Christ&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-cor/2.16?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Cor. 2:16</a>). This process can happily include, wrote Paul, those once &ldquo;alienated and enemies in [their] mind&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/col/1.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Col. 1:21</a>; see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/philip/2.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Philip. 2:5</a>). We can be so clever, like the adversary, and still not know the mind of God! (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/4.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 4:6</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p15" class="">We can be &ldquo;ever learning&rdquo; [<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/2-tim/3.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Tim. 3:7</a>] and yet allow the everlasting truths to get lost in life&rsquo;s shuffle as in this lamentation:</p>
			<div class="figure">
				<div class="stanza" id="">
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Where is the Life we have lost in living?</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Where is the wisdom we have lost in knowledge?</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Where is the knowledge we have lost in information?</span>
	  </div>
				</div>
				<div class="citationInfo" id="">
					<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p19" class="">(T. S. Eliot, &ldquo;Choruses from &lsquo;The Rock,&rsquo;&rdquo; in <span class="emphasis">The Complete Poems and Plays, 1909&ndash;1950,</span> New York: Harcourt, Brace, and World, 1971, p. 96).</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p20" class="">To help us become true disciples, the Lord has given us prophets and scriptures to strengthen us, &ldquo;to prepare the weak for those things which are coming on the earth, and for the Lord&rsquo;s errand in the day when &hellip; by the weak things of the earth the Lord shall thrash the nations by the power of his Spirit&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/133.58-59?lang=eng#57" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 133:58&ndash;59</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p21" class="">Feasting upon the fulness of the gospel will help us to overcome. Additionally, if we will keep our covenants, the covenants will keep us spiritually safe.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p22" class="">One day, and why not soon, the people of the Church will fulfill this prophecy: &ldquo;The power of the Lamb of God &hellip; descended upon the saints of the church of the Lamb, &hellip; the covenant people of the Lord, who were scattered upon all the face of the earth; and they were armed with righteousness and with the power of God in great glory&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/14.14?lang=eng#13" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 14:14</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p23" class="">However, our collective light does not yet shine brightly enough to be &ldquo;a standard for the nations&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/115.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 115:5</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p24" class="">The Church would grow much faster now, numerically and spiritually, if it were not for the wickedness of the world (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/14.12?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 14:12</a>). It would also grow much faster if you and I were better by taking up the Christian cross daily (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/luke/9.23?lang=eng#22" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Luke 9:23</a>). Part of taking up the cross is denying ourselves the lusts and appetites of the flesh. &ldquo;For it is better,&rdquo; the resurrected Jesus said, &ldquo;that ye should deny yourselves of these things, wherein ye will take up your cross&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/12.30?lang=eng#29" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 12:30</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p25" class="">Thus, the <span class="emphasis">daily</span> taking up of the cross means <span class="emphasis">daily</span> denying ourselves the appetites of the flesh.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p26" class="">By emulating the Master, who endured temptations but &ldquo;gave no heed unto them,&rdquo; [<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/20.22?lang=eng#21" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 20:22</a>] we, too, can live in a world filled with temptations &ldquo;such as [are] common to man&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-cor/10.13?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Cor. 10:13</a>). Of course Jesus noticed the tremendous temptations that came to him, but He did not process and reprocess them. Instead, He rejected them promptly. If we entertain temptations, soon they begin entertaining us! Turning these unwanted lodgers away at the doorstep of the mind is one way of giving &ldquo;no heed.&rdquo; Besides, these would-be lodgers are actually barbarians who, if admitted, can be evicted only with great trauma.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p27" class="">In a decaying environment, the mind is the last redoubt of righteousness, and it must be preserved even amid bombardment by evil stimuli. Christ is competent to see us through, &ldquo;for in that he himself hath suffered being tempted, he is able to succour them that are tempted&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/heb/2.18?lang=eng#17" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Heb. 2:18</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p28" class="">As promised, He will make either &ldquo;a way to escape&rdquo; or a way &ldquo;to bear it&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-cor/10.13?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Cor. 10:13</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p29" class="">We surely have been warned and forewarned about our time, a period in which the compression of challenges may make a year seem like a decade. Members will be cleverly mocked and scorned by those in the &ldquo;great and spacious building,&rdquo; representing the pride of the world (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/8.26?lang=eng#25" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 8:26</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/11.36?lang=eng#35" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 11:36</a>). No matter, for ere long, He who was raised on the third day will raze that spacious but third-class hotel!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p30" class="">Ours will be a time of great inversion as well as perversion, as some will call good evil and evil good (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/isa/5.20?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Isa. 5:20</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/15.20?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 15:20</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/64.16?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 64:16</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/2.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 2:5</a>). Others, in their ignorance of spiritual truths, will &ldquo;speak evil of those things which they know not&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/jude/1.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Jude 1:10</a>; see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/2-pet/2.12?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Pet. 2:12</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p31" class="">Peace has already been taken from the earth (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/1.35?lang=eng#34" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 1:35</a>). Nation will rise against nation (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/24.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 24:7</a>). It will also be a time of hardening as the love of many waxes cold and iniquity abounds (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/45.27?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 45:27</a>). Secular bewilderment will be epidemic amid the &ldquo;distress of nations, with perplexity&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/luke/21.25?lang=eng#24" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Luke 21:25</a>) as various vexations will mock man&rsquo;s cosmetic remedies:</p>
			<div class="figure">
				<div class="stanza" id="">
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">How small, of all that human hearts endure,</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">That part which laws or kings can cause or cure!</span>
	  </div>
				</div>
				<div class="citationInfo" id="">
					<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p34" class="">(Samuel Johnson, &ldquo;Lines added to Goldsmith&rsquo;s Traveller,&rdquo; in <span class="emphasis">Familiar Quotations,</span> comp. John Bartlett, Boston: Little, Brown, and Company, 1968, p. 428).</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p35" class="">We cannot expect to live in such a world without experiencing certain consequences of these conditions. Yet we can always keep our covenants, even if we cannot keep such conditions from coming.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p36" class="">The Lord, who knows all that through which we will pass, will help us to overcome in our &ldquo;small moment&rdquo; of time (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/122.4?lang=eng#3" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 122:4</a>). If we are settled, we will &ldquo;endure it well&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/121.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 121:8</a>) and &ldquo;hold fast&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-thes/5.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Thes. 5:21</a>). Endured righteously, &ldquo;all these things shall give [us] experience, and shall be for [our] good&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/122.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 122:7</a>). &ldquo;Think it not strange&rdquo; when disciples are called upon to pass through &ldquo;the fiery trial,&rdquo; said Peter (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-pet/4.12?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Pet. 4:12</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p37" class="">Even so, the Saints of God, as prophesied, will eventually &ldquo;cry unto the Lord day and night until deliverance comes&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">Prophetic Sayings of Heber C. Kimball,</span> n.p., n.d., p. 6).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p38" class="">The spiritually settled will finally overcome, and the glorious promise is, &ldquo;To him that overcometh will I grant to sit with me in my throne, even as I also overcame, and am set down with my Father in his throne&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/rev/3.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Rev. 3:21</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p39" class="">Meanwhile, let us remember &ldquo;what manner of persons [we] ought &hellip; to be&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/2-pet/3.11?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Pet. 3:11</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/27.27?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 27:27</a>). Attributively, we are to become even as Jesus, with His virtues being increasingly replicated in our lives. Even in the midst of our obvious imperfections, a sacred process is to be underway&mdash;if slowly, nevertheless resolutely. Whatever one&rsquo;s unfolding agendum, he can be <span class="emphasis">overcoming</span> if he is <span class="emphasis">becoming</span> more like Christ!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p40" class="">Even though scarred by the past, if contrite, Jesus&rsquo; promise is: &ldquo;I shall heal them&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/18.32?lang=eng#31" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 18:32</a>). Such shall become &ldquo;alive again&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/luke/15.32?lang=eng#31" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Luke 15:32</a>) &ldquo;in Christ because of [their] faith&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/25.25?lang=eng#24" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 25:25</a>). As part of His infinite atonement, Jesus knows &ldquo;according to the flesh&rdquo; all that through which we pass (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/7.11-12?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 7:11&ndash;12</a>). He has borne the sins, griefs, sorrows, and, declared Jacob, the pains of every man, woman, and child (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/9.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 9:21</a>). Having been perfected in His empathy, Jesus thus knows how to succor us.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p41" class="">We can, therefore, actually do as Peter urged and cast our cares upon the Lord (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-pet/5.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Pet. 5:7</a>); He is familiar with them, including even the feeling of being forsaken (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/mark/14.50?lang=eng#49" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mark 14:50</a>, <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/mark/15.34?lang=eng#33" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mark 15:34</a>). Nothing is beyond His redeeming reach or His encircling empathy. Therefore, we should not complain about our own life&rsquo;s not being a rose garden when we remember who wore the crown of thorns!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p42" class="">I turn now to the conclusion of Jesus&rsquo; mortal Messiahship. Luke reported Jesus&rsquo; sweating in Gethsemane &ldquo;as it were great drops of blood falling down to the ground&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/luke/22.44?lang=eng#43" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Luke 22:44</a>). This fact is fully validated in the &ldquo;other books&rdquo; of restoration scripture (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/13.39-40?lang=eng#38" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 13:39&ndash;40</a>): &ldquo;Which suffering caused myself, even God, the greatest of all, &hellip; to bleed at every pore, and to suffer both body and spirit&mdash;and would that I might not drink the bitter cup, and shrink&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/19.18?lang=eng#17" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 19:18</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p43" class="">The necessary but awesome shedding of Jesus&rsquo; blood thus occurred not only in the severe scourging, but earlier in Gethsemane. A recent and thoughtful article by several physicians on the physical death of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a> indicates that &ldquo;the severe scourging, with its intense pain and appreciable blood loss, most probably left Jesus in a preshock state.&rdquo; (We all recall, of course, that a dramatically weakened Jesus needed help to carry the cross.) &ldquo;Therefore, even before the actual crucifixion, Jesus&rsquo; physical condition was at least serious and possibly critical. &hellip; Although scourging may have resulted in considerable blood loss, crucifixion per se was a relatively bloodless procedure&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">Journal of the American Medical Association,</span> 21 Mar. 1986, pp. 1458, 1461).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p44" class="">In addition to the consequences of scourging, how Christ&rsquo;s lifeblood had already flowed in Gethsemane! Remember, he suffered &ldquo;both body and spirit&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/19.18?lang=eng#17" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 19:18</a>). Declared King Benjamin, Christ would suffer &ldquo;even more than man can suffer, except it be unto death; for behold, blood cometh from every pore, so great shall be his anguish&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/3.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 3:7</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p45" class="">Having bled at every pore, how red His raiment must have been in Gethsemane, how crimson that cloak!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p46" class="">No wonder, when Christ comes in power and glory, that He will come in reminding red attire (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/133.48?lang=eng#47" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 133:48</a>), signifying not only the winepress of wrath, but also to bring to our remembrance how He suffered for each of us in Gethsemane and on Calvary!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p47" class="">In recent years, as I have sung the hymns of the Atonement, it has been with an especially full heart&mdash;and also with full voice, when I can continue to sing&mdash;lines such as &ldquo;How great thou art,&rdquo; &ldquo;I scarce can take it in,&rdquo; &ldquo;To rescue a soul so rebellious and proud as mine,&rdquo; &ldquo;I stand all amazed,&rdquo; and &ldquo;Oh, it is wonderful!&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">Hymns,</span> 1985, nos. 86, 193).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p48" class="">Now, my brothers and sisters, let not Jesus&rsquo; redemption for us stop at the immortalizing dimension of the Atonement, &ldquo;the loosing of the bands of death&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/11.41?lang=eng#40" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 11:41</a>). Let us grasp the proffered gift of eternal life! We will end up either choosing Christ&rsquo;s manner of living or His manner of suffering! It is either &ldquo;suffer even as I&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/19.16-17?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 19:16&ndash;17</a>), or overcome &ldquo;even as [He] &hellip; overcame&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/rev/3.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Rev. 3:21</a>). His beckoning command is to become &ldquo;even as I am&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/27.27?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 27:27</a>). The spiritually settled accept that invitation, and &ldquo;through the atonement of Christ,&rdquo; they <span class="emphasis">become</span> and <span class="emphasis">overcome!</span> (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/3.18-19?lang=eng#17" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 3:18&ndash;19</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1987/05/overcome-even-as-i-also-overcame.p49" class="">In this unsettled world, may we settle in our hearts on this determination, I pray in the holy name of Jesus Christ, amen.</p>
		
                            
                            
                            
